history.content:
Can't speak to 168 as I'm not taking it til this fall, but between 186 and 100 I'd definitely say 186 is more useful for industry. While 186 is definitely less "fun" than 100 in terms of projects and topics covered, I've found that databases knowledge is a lot more widely used when in comparison to basic data science.

However, this is all subjective to what you want to go into after graduation. I suppose the tools from 100 (numpy, pandas, matplotlib/seaborn, etc.) are useful if you're going into data science roles, but if you're just going into general software engineering then definitely do 186.

history.content: I'm a CS minor and this fall semester is my last. I'm trying to decide between CS 168, 181, and 100 for my last CS upper-div. The two other upper-divs I have taken are 161 and 160 (summer). I found 161 to be difficult and very time-consuming last semester and because I'll also be recruiting, I want to find a class with lighter workload (and on a fairly easier side conceptually). Also, I'm looking for a class that may be useful for when I go into the industry after graduation. For 100, I have not taken Data 8 or any classes on statistics before. I'll be taking CS 70 along with the upper-div.
